		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>California <hi rend="underline">San Fran</hi></placeName> <date>May 29 1862</date></p>
				<p>Reply to &#8220;Wrong doings in <placeName>California</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Editor of the Occident</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Revd. Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">My attention has<lb/> been drawn to the above article in the<lb/> gleaner of the <date>23d</date> Inst. copied from<lb/> the Occident of <date>April 62</date>&#8212;in which it<lb/> states &#8220;Two <persName>C<hi rend="underline">ohamin</hi></persName> applied to<lb/> congregation &#8220;Sherith Israel&#8221; to be mar&#45;<lb/>&#45;ried by <persName>Dr. Henry</persName> to widows&#44; and<lb/> he refused.&#8221;  <persName>Theophilis</persName> &#40;upon whom<lb/> I suspect I could lay my finger&#41;<lb/> does <hi rend="underline">not</hi> tell the Truth.  <hi rend="underline">I</hi> am the<lb/> wife of one of the &#8220;<persName>Cohanim</persName>&#8221; alluded<lb/> to&#44; and beg to state the facts to<lb/> you.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I arrived in <placeName>California</placeName> in <date>1850</date>&#44; and<lb/> in the spring of <date>1852</date> left with my<lb/> first husband on a trading voyage<lb/> to the <placeName>South Pacific Islands</placeName>&#44; and</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p rend="align(center)">2</p>
				<p>unfortunately lost him at one of the<lb/> Tonga<add>&#63;</add> group in <date>September 1852</date>l&#44; I returned<lb/> to this city <date>Dec. 27<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> of the same year<lb/> dreadfully distressed in mind&#8212;in<lb/> fact inconsolable.  My Father &#40;god rest<lb/> his dear soul&#41; was here till <date>July 1854</date><lb/> during that period he made the ac&#45;<lb/>&#45;quaintance of <persName>Mr. P.</persName> and wished me<lb/> very much to marry him.  I told<lb/> him no&#8212;but so anxious was<lb/> he&#44; that&#44; previous to his departure for<lb/> <placeName>New York</placeName> he left word with a friend<lb/> to occasionally urge the matter to me.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In <date>1858</date> I was engaged to<lb/> <persName>Mr. P.</persName> but called his attention to Chap. 21<lb/> V. 14 of Leviticus&#58; he said he would con&#45;<lb/>&#45;sult a <hi rend="underline">Lamdan</hi>&#44; which he did&#44; and<lb/> this gentleman said&#44; <hi rend="underline">that</hi> passage<lb/> referred to the <hi rend="underline">High Priest</hi>&#33;  I was<lb/> satisfied and our engagement<lb/> went on&#44; to the knowledge more or<lb/> less of nearly all the Jews in the</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p rend="align(center)">3</p>
				<p>city&#44; for <persName>Mr. P.</persName> and myself regularly attended<lb/> synagogue during that period we<lb/> visited at <persName>Dr. Henry&#39;s</persName> certainly <hi rend="underline">once</hi> a<lb/> week &#40;many times more frequently&#41; and he&#44; and the<lb/> late <persName>Mrs. Henry</persName> used repeatedly ask what<lb/> we visited for&#63;  On the <date>15<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of Feb.<lb/> 1859</date> <persName>Mr. P.</persName> applied to the Board of the<lb/> Congregation &#8220;Sherith Israel&#8221; for permission<lb/> to marry&#8212;which was granted and&#44;<lb/> <hi rend="underline"><persName>Dr. Henry</persName> had written and fitted out</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">our Casubba</hi> a thing he subsequently<lb/> told us he very seldom did before the<lb/> day it was wanted.  So much for <persName>Dr<lb/> Henry&#39;s</persName> refusal&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">On the <date>24<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of Feb.</date> the day previous<lb/> to the one appointed for our marriage<lb/> <persName>Dr. Henry</persName> called at &#189; 7 A. M. and after<lb/> some slight circumlocution asked me<lb/> if my former Husband had Brothers&#63;<lb/>  <sic>at</sic> first I could not recollect&#44; I felt<lb/> confused and without knowing why<lb/> felt certain <persName>Dr. H</persName> had not come on<lb/> a friendly errand.  I said I believed<lb/> there were two but I was not sure</p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p rend="align(center)">4</p>
				<p>if there were more or not&#44; he asked me<lb/> if I had had &#8220;Halitza&#8221;&#63;  I replied &#8220;Doctor<lb/> you know that is not done any more at<lb/> home&#8221; I cannot help it &#8220;he said&#8221; a<lb/> man named <persName>Ephraim</persName> says he was at school<lb/> with a Brother of your husband&#39;s 17 years<lb/> ago&#44; a Trustee meeting has been held&#8212;the<lb/> Trustees leave it to me&#44; and I cannot<lb/> marry you.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">You may imagine my feelings<lb/> Revd. Sir&#44; I had been in <placeName>California</placeName><lb/> nearly 10 years&#44; had been a widow 7&#44;<lb/> had shown a good example and<lb/> felt dreadfully aggrieved to be so served<lb/> at the last moment.  <persName>Mr. P.</persName> said &#8220;never<lb/> mind we will go to a Magistrate&#8221;<lb/> I replied no&#8212;I am very angry<lb/> now&#44; in an hour I shall be more com&#45;<lb/>&#45;posed&#44; I will go round to <persName>Dr. Henry</persName><lb/> and ask him these questions&#44; if he<lb/> answers me satisfactorily we will marry&#8212;<lb/>if not&#44; we part.  I will never see you<lb/> again&#8212;if you please you may</p>
		
			<div>
				<p><ref target="Occident_PDFs/Occ_20_1.pdf">The above text refers to Occident Volume 20 No. 1 pages 15 through 19. Click here to view.</ref></p>
			</div>
